data.title: Timeless Tickets: Sonny & Cher brought 'the threat of pandemonium' to Davenport in 1965
data.meta_description: In 1965, Sonny & Cher played in Davenport, years before their TV show debuted. We revisited the Times-Democrat review of the concert.
data.text:
By the mid-60s, Beatlemania had taken over popular music culture.

But for one night in Davenport, Sonny & Cher mania reigned supreme.

The husband-wife pop duo played a show at RKO Orpheum Theater on November 16, 1965. Times-Democrat reporter Pat Welch was tasked with reviewing the gig at the time.

"Even before Sonny & Cher, at the very top of 'pop' today, took the stage, there was the ever-present threat of pandemonium," she wrote.

Sonny & Cher played two shows that Tuesday night, one at 6:30 p.m. and another at 9 p.m. The review ran in the paper the next day, with vignettes from a crowd full of teenage superfans.

"The boys and girls in the audience crept forward inch by inch, some of them knelt, leaning on the railing of the orchestra pit with hands folded and eyes reverent, as if it were a communion rail," she wrote.

"Cher wore a pair of lime green pants that looked like they had to have been applied with spray paint — flared for her feet to get in and out of — with a lime green and black harlequin top."

Welch went on to describe the madness outside the venue, noting fans pushing past police officers in full riot gear just to get an autograph. Earlier that afternoon, a group of young girls even snuck into the Hotel Blackhawk to find Sonny & Cher's hotel room.

"The girls sat on the bed in the purple-draped 'Trianon' room and listened in awe," Welch wrote.

Times-Democrat spoke with duo

Perhaps most impressively, Welch also spoke with Sonny & Cher via phone interview before the show. Presumably, they spoke after the show, too, as Welch quoted Sonny in her review of the concert.

"We're not like the Life magazine made us out to be," Sonny told Welch at the time. "We don't have matching sports cars. My car is an old Cadillac. Our house is a luxury, but not extreme — only three bedrooms."

It would be easy to believe otherwise.

After all, the pop duo charted in the Billboard Hot 100 five times in 1965 alone. They were at the peak of their fame. Just months before the show, their single "I Got You Babe" was the biggest song in the country.

At the time of their show in Davenport, Sonny & Cher had two songs in the Top 75: "The Letter" and "But You're Mine."

Then, there were the contract demands. Times-Democrat columnist Jim Arpy noted earlier that month, after an interview with RKO Orpheum Theater manager Milt Troehler, that the married duo had a few requests.

"A strange contract," Troehler remarked to Arpy, pointing out that Sonny & Cher requested a seven-passenger limousine, strict instructions for their security detail, a separate car for luggage, a recliner, a couch and hot tea and coffee at the ready.

"When you gross $4 million a year, you can afford to be strange."

Arpy prophesized that Sonny & Cher were on their way to "out-Beatling the Beatles."

One of the openers for the show was Danny Hutton. Two years later, he co-founded the vocal trio Three Dog Night.

In their phone interview with Welch, Sonny & Cher said that they'd never been to Iowa before. Welch noted in the preview story that Sonny & Cher — who wed in 1964, but later divorced in 1975 — would be celebrating their first anniversary in Davenport.

After the show, the duo disputed that claim.

"I don't know how that rumor got started about our anniversary," Sonny joked to the Times-Democrat. "I had to go out and buy her a present."

'If I Could Turn Back Time'

After their divorce, Sonny and Cher appeared together a few more times throughout the '70s and '80s, but ultimately went in opposite directions in their careers.

Cher has had various comebacks over the years, recurrently entering the public sphere with new hits and film appearances, perhaps none more significant than her late-80s single "If I Could Turn Back Time" and her late-90s hit "Believe."

Today, Cher is still one of the music world's easily recognizable mononyms.

Sonny, on the other hand, went into politics. He served a term as the mayor of Palm Springs, California, and around the same time Cher was preparing to top charts with "Believe," he was elected to the U.S. House of Representatives.

His term was cut short when he died in 1998 in a skiing accident. Cher spoke at his funeral, and his wife, Mary Bono, took his place in office, holding the seat until 2012.

But still, in their 1965 visit to Davenport, Sonny and Cher might as well have been the president and first lady.

"Sonny and Cher waved and smiled and blew kisses," wrote Welch, in the aftermath of the show.

"A teen girl who is ordinarily a calm and collected young miss stared at her right hand as if it had suddenly sprouted warts: 'Sonny touched me,' she said, stunned."

Sonny & Cher didn't have the only massive show in town that year. Also playing the Quad-Cities in 1965 was funk icon James Brown, who appeared at Davenport's Masonic Temple in August.

Rock Island music fanatic Larry Miller was at that James Brown gig, and called it the greatest show he's ever seen.

That's saying something, because three years after Brown's appearance in Davenport, Miller saw the one and only Jimi Hendrix, just up the road at Col. Ballroom.

This story is part of a series called "Timeless Tickets," where we're aiming to find the most notable concert in the Quad-Cities, every year from 1960 to today. Do you have a story or photo to share from an iconic local show? Send it to entertainment reporter Gannon Hanevold at ghanevold@qctimes.com.
